6","1132":"1132","1170":"1170","of Tyddyn Adda,Llanidan,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Llanidan, Anglesey, Wales":"Brynshenkin, Anglesey, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Angelesey Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Llanllawddog, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanllawddog, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1132–Male":"1132–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1246–Female":"1246–Deceased","1248–Male":"1248–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1170 to 1198":"from 1170 to 1198","about 1170":"about 1170","1248":"1248","1246":"1246","about 1248":"about 1248","about 1246":"about 1246","1132":"1132","1170":"1170","of Tyddyn Adda,Llanidan,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Llanidan, Anglesey, Wales":"Brynshenkin, Anglesey, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Angelesey Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Llanllawddog, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanllawddog, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gilman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a personal name, Old French <i>Guillemin</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>Willemin</i>, pet forms of <i>Guillelmes</i>, <i>Guillaumes</i>, and <i>Willelmes</i> (see   William  ).","Altered form of German <b>Gillmann</b> (see   Gillman  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Gillman","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Gilman  .","Americanized form of German <b>Gillmann</b>: variant of   Gille   2."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>William</i>, <i>Willam</i>, <i>Willem</i>, an Old Picard and Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Willihelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>wil-</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet, protection’. This Norman personal name became widely used in England, Scotland and Wales after the Conquest, mainly no doubt in honor of the Conqueror himself. By the 13th century it had already become the most popular personal name in England. A Parisian form of the name <i>Guillaume</i> was also sometimes used (see   Gillam  ), which in medieval Wales was adopted as <i>Gwilym</i> (see   Gwilliam  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Guillaume  ."]}]},{"name":"Adles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Manfred, Fritz, Gunther, Helmut, Klaus, Merwin, Otto, Bernhard, Egon.  Jewish Moshe, Ari, Arie, Aron, Emanuel, Hillel, Aryeh, Avi, Avram, Chaim.","German: from <i>Adler</i> ‘eagle’, in most cases a topographic or habitational name referring to a house identified by the sign of an eagle. The German noun is from Middle High German <i>adelar</i>, itself a compound of <i>adel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>ar</i> ‘eagle’. This surname is also found in e.g. Czechia, Poland, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of the Slavic surname   Orel  , in Hungary, where it is spelled <b>Ádler</b>, and in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name meaning ‘eagle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Eagle","meanings":["From Latin, the name borne in classical mythology by various characters—a daughter of the Sun and sister of Phaeton; one of the Hesperides; and a nymph, daughter of Jupiter and Neaera. It derives from the Greek word <i>aiglē</i> ‘brightness, splendour’."]},{"name":"Idler","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Adler   3 (see   Allard  ), altered by false association with the word <i>idler</i>.","German: perhaps an Americanized form of   Adler   1."]},{"name":"Orel","meanings":["Biblical name, apparently meaning ‘pine tree’ in Hebrew, mentioned in a genealogy (1 Chronicles 2:25). This name is in use in a number of different spellings. There may have been some confusion with the Irish name Oran , of which this is sometimes a variant spelling."]}]},{"name":"Verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Gronwy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of uncertain derivation, borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by  Goronwy the Staunch , Lord of Penllyn. He became the lover of the flower-maiden Blodeuedd and murdered her husband  Lleu Llaw Gyffes , but Lleu was later restored to life and definitively dispatched Goronwy."],"variants":[{"name":"Gronw","meanings":["Variant of   Goronwy ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adles Verch Gronwy Edynfed Gilman was born in Anglesey, Wales. She married Gronwy Ap Maredudd from 1170 to 1198, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in Wales."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1246–Female":"1246–Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1170 to 1198":"1170 kuni 1198","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1248":"1248","1246":"1246","about 1248":"umbes 1248","about 1246":"umbes 1246","1132":"1132","1170":"1170","of Tyddyn Adda,Llanidan,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Llanidan, Anglesey, Wales":"Brynshenkin, Anglesey, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Angelesey Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Llanllawddog, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanllawddog, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1132–Male":"1132–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1246–Female":"1246–Kuollut","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1170 to 1198":"vuod